OVERVIEW of A

Before using advanced methods, you need to develop a baseline understanding of the event probability as a function of the inputs using generalized linear modeling techniques. Use glm() to fit the following linear models: Categorical variables only linear additive Continuous variables only linear additive All categorical and continuous variables linear additive Interact region with continuous inputs, do not include customer Interact customer with continuous inputs, do not include region All pairwise interactions of continuous inputs, do not include categorical inputs 3 models with basis functions of your choice Can include interactions of the basis functions with other basis functions and with the categorical inputs! These models are consistent with the regression portion. Did you experience any issues or warnings while fitting the generalized linear models? Which of the 9 models is the best? What performance metric did you use to make your selection? Visualize the coefficient summaries for your top 3 models. How do the coefficient summaries compare between the top 3? explore the imbalance of data

df_all %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=outcome))+
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(y=stat(prop),group=1))+
  geom_text(data=df_all %>%count(outcome)%>%
              mutate(freq=n/sum(n)),
            mapping=aes(x=outcome,y=freq,label=signif(freq,3)),
            nudge_y=0.02,color='red')+
  theme_bw()

As we all know, if one class appears in less than 15% of the observations, we should be concerned about class imbalance. Based on the figure above, the event level is only 18% of the observations. Its very close to 15%, in this part Ill not deal with it.

my_ctrl<-trainControl(method="repeatedcv",number=5,repeats=3,
                      summaryFunction=twoClassSummary,
                      classProbs=TRUE,
                      savePredictions = TRUE)
my_metric<-'ROC'

Categorical variables only linear additive

set.seed(4321)
c_fit_glm_categorical_only <-train(outcome ~region+customer,
                            data=df_all,
                            method='glm',
                            metric=my_metric,
                            preProcess=c('center','scale'),
                            trControl=my_ctrl)

These models are consistent with the regression portion. Did you experience any issues or warnings while fitting the generalized linear models?

Yes I met three kins of warnings.
First Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred
Second Warning: glm.fit: algorithm did not converge
Third Warning: Warning in predict.lm(object, newdata, se.fit, scale = 1, type = if (type == : prediction from a rank-deficient fit may be misleading
For the first warning,
it might mean the predicted probabilities of one or more observations are indistinguishable from 0 or 1. To solve this, there are two ways. The first one is increasing the sample size, and the second one is removing outliers.
I tried to use preProcess method, and then the number of this kind of warning is decreasing, even some are still here.

For the second warning, it seems like the predictor variable is able to perfectly separate the response variable y into 0s and 1s, which answered by GOOGLE..To handle the warning, we can use penalized regression. For example, using glmnet.
For the third warning, this might due to the fact that some pairs of predictor variables are perfectly correlated. It can be solved by tuning some inputs.
